<ns2764:section xmlns:ns2764="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.concepts.architecture.mda.baseTechnologies.mof.howIsMofRepresented">

  <ns2765:title xmlns:ns2765="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">How is MOF represented?</ns2765:title> 
  <ns2766:para xmlns:ns2766="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    MOF provides a consistent way to define language constructs. For example, for 
    <ns2767:emphasis xmlns:ns2767="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">work flow modeling</ns2767:emphasis> one needs the concepts of
    <ns2768:itemizedlist xmlns:ns2768="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns2769:listitem xmlns:ns2769="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2770:para xmlns:ns2770="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">activity,</ns2770:para></ns2769:listitem>
      <ns2771:listitem xmlns:ns2771="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2772:para xmlns:ns2772="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">worker,</ns2772:para></ns2771:listitem>
      <ns2773:listitem xmlns:ns2773="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2774:para xmlns:ns2774="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">transition,</ns2774:para></ns2773:listitem>
      <ns2775:listitem xmlns:ns2775="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2776:para xmlns:ns2776="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">split,</ns2776:para></ns2775:listitem>
      <ns2777:listitem xmlns:ns2777="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2778:para xmlns:ns2778="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">join, and so on.</ns2778:para></ns2777:listitem>
    </ns2768:itemizedlist>
  </ns2766:para>
  <ns2779:para xmlns:ns2779="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    On the other hand, for <ns2780:emphasis xmlns:ns2780="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">relational database modeling</ns2780:emphasis>
    we need the concepts of 
    <ns2781:itemizedlist xmlns:ns2781="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns2782:listitem xmlns:ns2782="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2783:para xmlns:ns2783="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">table,</ns2783:para></ns2782:listitem>
      <ns2784:listitem xmlns:ns2784="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2785:para xmlns:ns2785="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">row,</ns2785:para></ns2784:listitem>
      <ns2786:listitem xmlns:ns2786="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2787:para xmlns:ns2787="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">key,</ns2787:para></ns2786:listitem>
      <ns2788:listitem xmlns:ns2788="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2789:para xmlns:ns2789="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">column,</ns2789:para></ns2788:listitem>
      <ns2790:listitem xmlns:ns2790="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2791:para xmlns:ns2791="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">link, and so on.</ns2791:para></ns2790:listitem>
    </ns2781:itemizedlist>
  </ns2779:para>
  <ns2792:para xmlns:ns2792="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    MOF is itself based on the fundamental premise of object-oriented modeling
    has the ability to specify a new domain by
    <ns2793:itemizedlist xmlns:ns2793="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns2794:listitem xmlns:ns2794="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2795:para xmlns:ns2795="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">introducing new concepts (classes),</ns2795:para></ns2794:listitem>
      <ns2796:listitem xmlns:ns2796="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2797:para xmlns:ns2797="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">assign attributes and operations to these concepts,</ns2797:para></ns2796:listitem>
      <ns2798:listitem xmlns:ns2798="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2799:para xmlns:ns2799="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        and building up relationships like
        <ns2800:itemizedlist xmlns:ns2800="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
          <ns2801:listitem xmlns:ns2801="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2802:para xmlns:ns2802="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">containment,</ns2802:para></ns2801:listitem>
          <ns2803:listitem xmlns:ns2803="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2804:para xmlns:ns2804="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">specialization and abstraction,</ns2804:para></ns2803:listitem>
          <ns2805:listitem xmlns:ns2805="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2806:para xmlns:ns2806="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">association/uses</ns2806:para></ns2805:listitem>
        </ns2800:itemizedlist>
        between the concepts</ns2799:para></ns2798:listitem>
    </ns2793:itemizedlist>
  </ns2792:para>
  
  <ns2807:para xmlns:ns2807="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    As such Mof also uses the concepts of classes, attributes, associations and so on.
    UML 2.0 and MOF 2.0 now share a common kernel and as such MOF diagrams look very
    similar to UML diagrams and can be generated by a UML tool. Furthermore, like UML,
    MOF also supports the <ns2808:emphasis xmlns:ns2808="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Object Constraint Language</ns2808:emphasis>, OCL.
    The <ns2809:emphasis xmlns:ns2809="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">unified modeling language</ns2809:emphasis>, UML, is itself specified via MOF. 
    For example, in
    <ns2810:xref xmlns:ns2810="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" linkend="resources.information.concepts.architecture.mda.baseTechnologies.mof.mofUmlClassDiagram_fig"/>
    we show a fragment of the UML's metamodel for class diagrams.
  </ns2807:para>
  
  <ns2811:figure xmlns:ns2811="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.concepts.architecture.mda.baseTechnologies.mof.mofUmlClassDiagram_fig">
    <ns2812:title xmlns:ns2812="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">MOF used to specify a fragment of the metamodel for UML class diagrams</ns2812:title>
    <mediaobject xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><imageobject><imagedata fileref="mofUmlClassDiagram.jpg"/></imageobject></mediaobject>
  </ns2811:figure>
  
  <ns2813:para xmlns:ns2813="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    This object-oriented conceptualization is equally applicable for domains which are not
    perceived to be object-oriented. For example, relational database structures and even
    the syntax of object-oriented and non-object-oriented programming languages can be
    specified in MOF. MOF itself is then also used to specify the <ns2814:emphasis xmlns:ns2814="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Common
    Warehouse Metamodel</ns2814:emphasis> (CWM) and the <ns2815:emphasis xmlns:ns2815="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">XML Metadata
    Interchange</ns2815:emphasis> (XMI) modeling languages.
    <ns2816:note xmlns:ns2816="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2817:para xmlns:ns2817="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      Sun's Java Community Process (JCP) has developed a MOF-Java mapping, the
      <ns2818:emphasis xmlns:ns2818="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java Metadata Interface</ns2818:emphasis>.
    </ns2817:para></ns2816:note>
  </ns2813:para>
  <ns2819:para xmlns:ns2819="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    As another example of MOF, look at the fragment of the metamodel for UML use case diagrams
    shown in <ns2820:xref xmlns:ns2820="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" linkend="resources.information.concepts.architecture.mda.baseTechnologies.mof.mofUmlUseCaseDiagram_fig"/>.
  </ns2819:para>
  
  <ns2821:figure xmlns:ns2821="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.concepts.architecture.mda.baseTechnologies.mof.mofUmlUseCaseDiagram_fig">
    <ns2822:title xmlns:ns2822="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">MOF used to specify a fragment of the metamodel for UML use case diagrams</ns2822:title>
    <mediaobject xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><imageobject><imagedata fileref="mofUmlUseCaseDiagram.jpg"/></imageobject></mediaobject>
  </ns2821:figure>
</ns2764:section>